function _sfc_render(_ctx, _cache, $props, $setup, $data, $options) {
  return openBlock(), createElementBlock("div", null, [..._cache[0] || (_cache[0] = [
    createStaticVNode('<h1 id="federation-materialization-realtime-views-and-write-paths" tabindex="-1">Federation, Materialization, Realtime Views, and Write Paths <a class="header-anchor" href="#federation-materialization-realtime-views-and-write-paths" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Federation, Materialization, Realtime Views, and Write Paths&quot;">​</a></h1><p>FlashQL lets you treat local and origin data as one relational graph while still controlling:</p><ul><li>what stays runtime-only</li><li>what gets cached locally</li><li>what stays continuously synchronized</li><li>and how writes made against local views travel back to the origin</li></ul><p>This entire system is built around views.</p><h2 id="start-with-the-mental-model" tabindex="-1">Start with the mental model <a class="header-anchor" href="#start-with-the-mental-model" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Start with the mental model&quot;">​</a></h2><p>In FlashQL, a view is not only a query convenience.</p><p>For federation and sync, a view becomes the contract between:</p><ul><li>your local app-facing database surface</li><li>and some origin relation that may live elsewhere</li></ul><p>That means one view definition can answer all of these questions at once:</p><ul><li>where does this data come from?</li><li>should it stay runtime-only, be materialized, or stay realtime?</li><li>can I write to it locally?</li><li>if I can write to it, how should local state behave before the origin acknowledges?</li></ul><p>So this page is really about one thing:</p><blockquote><p>how a local relational view becomes the boundary between your app and an origin database</p></blockquote><h2 id="the-two-ingredients" tabindex="-1">The two ingredients <a class="header-anchor" href="#the-two-ingredients" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;The two ingredients&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Two things work together to form the foreign I/O system:</p><ol><li>a local database view that points to an origin relation</li><li>an upstream client instance that knows how to talk to that origin</li></ol><p>At a high level:</p><ol><li>the view defines how origin data should appear locally</li><li>the upstream client lets FlashQL talk to the origin behind that view</li></ol><h2 id="ordinary-local-views-first" tabindex="-1">Ordinary local views first <a class="header-anchor" href="#ordinary-local-views-first" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Ordinary local views first&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Start with the ordinary database idea:</p><div class="language-js"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang">js</span><pre class="shiki material-theme-palenight vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;font-style:italic;">await</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> db</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">.</span><span style="color:#82AAFF;">query</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">(</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">`</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  CREATE VIEW public.posts AS</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  SELECT title, content FROM public.blog</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;">`</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">)</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">;</span></span></code></pre></div><p>Above, querying <code>public.posts</code> resolves against <code>public.blog</code> in the local database.</p><p>That is just a normal view.</p><h2 id="turning-a-view-into-an-origin-backed-view" tabindex="-1">Turning a view into an origin-backed view <a class="header-anchor" href="#turning-a-view-into-an-origin-backed-view" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Turning a view into an origin-backed view&quot;">​</a></h2><p>FlashQL extends that idea so the same view surface can resolve from an origin outside the local database.</p><div class="language-js"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang">js</span><pre class="shiki material-theme-palenight vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;font-style:italic;">await</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> db</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">.</span><span style="color:#82AAFF;">query</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">(</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">`</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  CREATE VIEW public.posts AS</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  SELECT title, content FROM public.blog</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  WITH (replication_origin = &#39;postgres:primary&#39;)</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;">`</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">)</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">;</span></span></code></pre></div><p>Now the local view can be read as:</p><div class="language-js"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang">js</span><pre class="shiki material-theme-palenight vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;font-style:italic;">await</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> db</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">.</span><span style="color:#82AAFF;">query</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">(</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">`</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  SELECT * FROM public.posts;</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;">`</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">)</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">;</span></span></code></pre></div><p>and still participate in local relational work such as joins:</p><div class="language-js"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang">js</span><pre class="shiki material-theme-palenight vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;font-style:italic;">await</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> db</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">.</span><span style="color:#82AAFF;">query</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">(</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">`</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  SELECT *</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  FROM public.posts</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  LEFT JOIN public.users ON posts.user_id = users.id;</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;">`</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">)</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">;</span></span></code></pre></div><p>The query executes as one relational graph, but composed of both local and origin data.</p><h2 id="the-upstream-client-factory" tabindex="-1">The upstream client factory <a class="header-anchor" href="#the-upstream-client-factory" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;The upstream client factory&quot;">​</a></h2><p>To talk to an origin, FlashQL needs an upstream client instance.</p><p>That is provided through <code>getUpstreamClient()</code>:</p><div class="language-js"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang">js</span><pre class="shiki material-theme-palenight vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;font-style:italic;">import</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;"> {</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> FlashQL</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;"> }</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;font-style:italic;"> from</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;"> &#39;</span><span style="color:#C3E88D;">@linked-db/linked-ql/flashql</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">&#39;</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">;</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;font-style:italic;">import</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;"> {</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> EdgeClient</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;"> }</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;font-style:italic;"> from</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;"> &#39;</span><span style="color:#C3E88D;">@linked-db/linked-ql/edge</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">&#39;</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">;</span></span>\n<span class="line"></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C792EA;">const</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> db </span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">=</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;"> new</span><span style="color:#82AAFF;"> FlashQL</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">(</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">{</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C792EA;">  async</span><span style="color:#F07178;"> getUpstreamClient</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">(</span><span style="color:#BABED8;font-style:italic;">originId</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">)</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;"> {</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;font-style:italic;">    if</span><span style="color:#F07178;"> (</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">originId</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;"> !==</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;"> &#39;</span><span style="color:#C3E88D;">postgres:primary</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">&#39;</span><span style="color:#F07178;">) </span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">{</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;font-style:italic;">      throw</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;"> new</span><span style="color:#82AAFF;"> Error</span><span style="color:#F07178;">(</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">`</span><span style="color:#C3E88D;">Unknown origin: </span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">${</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">originId</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">}`</span><span style="color:#F07178;">)</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">;</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;">    }</span></span>\n<span class="line"></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;font-style:italic;">    return</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;"> new</span><span style="color:#82AAFF;"> EdgeClient</span><span style="color:#F07178;">(</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">{</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#F07178;">      url</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">:</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;"> &#39;</span><span style="color:#C3E88D;">/api/db</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">&#39;</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">,</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#F07178;">      dialect</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">:</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;"> &#39;</span><span style="color:#C3E88D;">postgres</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">&#39;</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">,</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;">    }</span><span style="color:#F07178;">)</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">;</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;">  },</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;">}</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">)</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">;</span></span>\n<span class="line"></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;font-style:italic;">await</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> db</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">.</span><span style="color:#82AAFF;">connect</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">()</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">;</span></span></code></pre></div><p>This is now a local FlashQL instance that can resolve origin-backed views on demand.</p><p>The important idea is that <code>replication_origin</code> does not have to be the network URL itself. It is the origin id that your app uses to choose the right upstream client.</p><h2 id="replication-origin" tabindex="-1"><code>replication_origin</code> <a class="header-anchor" href="#replication-origin" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;`replication_origin`&quot;">​</a></h2><p><code>replication_origin</code> is the switch that makes a view origin-backed.</p><p>If it is absent or <code>NULL</code>, the view behaves like an ordinary local view.</p><p>If it is present, FlashQL resolves the view through an upstream client.</p><h3 id="the-current-contract" tabindex="-1">The current contract <a class="header-anchor" href="#the-current-contract" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;The current contract&quot;">​</a></h3><p>At the view level, <code>replication_origin</code> is expected to be one of:</p><ul><li>a dialect-prefixed origin id such as <code>postgres:primary</code> or <code>flashql:primary</code></li><li><code>INHERIT</code>, meaning &quot;use the schema-level default origin&quot;</li><li><code>NULL</code>, meaning &quot;this view is not origin-backed&quot;</li></ul><p>Examples:</p><div class="language-sql"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang">sql</span><pre class="shiki material-theme-palenight vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span style="color:#F78C6C;">WITH</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> (replication_origin </span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">=</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;"> &#39;</span><span style="color:#C3E88D;">postgres:primary</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">&#39;</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">)</span></span></code></pre></div><div class="language-sql"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang">sql</span><pre class="shiki material-theme-palenight vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span style="color:#F78C6C;">WITH</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> (replication_origin </span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">=</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> INHERIT)</span></span></code></pre></div><div class="language-sql"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang">sql</span><pre class="shiki material-theme-palenight vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span style="color:#F78C6C;">WITH</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> (replication_origin </span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">=</span><span style="color:#F78C6C;"> NULL</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">)</span></span></code></pre></div><p>The important thing is the dialect prefix. That prefix gives FlashQL enough information to choose the right origin adapter family.</p><h2 id="schema-level-default-origins" tabindex="-1">Schema-level default origins <a class="header-anchor" href="#schema-level-default-origins" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Schema-level default origins&quot;">​</a></h2><p>If many views in one schema point at the same origin, you do not want to repeat that id everywhere.</p><p>FlashQL supports a schema-level default through <code>default_replication_origin</code>:</p><div class="language-js"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang">js</span><pre class="shiki material-theme-palenight vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;font-style:italic;">await</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> db</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">.</span><span style="color:#82AAFF;">query</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">(</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">`</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  CREATE SCHEMA remote</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  WITH (default_replication_origin = &#39;postgres:primary&#39;)</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;">`</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">)</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">;</span></span></code></pre></div><p>You can also alter it later:</p><div class="language-js"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang">js</span><pre class="shiki material-theme-palenight vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;font-style:italic;">await</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> db</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">.</span><span style="color:#82AAFF;">query</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">(</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">`</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  ALTER SCHEMA remote</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  SET (default_replication_origin = &#39;postgres:primary&#39;)</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;">`</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">)</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">;</span></span></code></pre></div><p>Then individual views can inherit that origin:</p><div class="language-js"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang">js</span><pre class="shiki material-theme-palenight vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;font-style:italic;">await</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> db</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">.</span><span style="color:#82AAFF;">query</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">(</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">`</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  CREATE VIEW remote.posts AS</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  SELECT * FROM public.posts</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  WITH (replication_origin = INHERIT)</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;">`</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">)</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">;</span></span></code></pre></div><p>So:</p><ul><li><code>default_replication_origin</code> is the schema-level default</li><li><code>replication_origin = INHERIT</code> is the view-level inheritance hook</li></ul><h2 id="replication-modes" tabindex="-1">Replication modes <a class="header-anchor" href="#replication-modes" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Replication modes&quot;">​</a></h2><p>A view&#39;s replication mode decides how origin data should behave locally.</p><p>Values can be:</p><ul><li><code>none</code></li><li><code>materialized</code></li><li><code>realtime</code></li></ul><h3 id="runtime-views" tabindex="-1">Runtime views <a class="header-anchor" href="#runtime-views" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Runtime views&quot;">​</a></h3><p>Runtime views are the default.</p><div class="language-js"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang">js</span><pre class="shiki material-theme-palenight vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;font-style:italic;">await</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> db</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">.</span><span style="color:#82AAFF;">query</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">(</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">`</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  CREATE VIEW public.users AS</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  SELECT * FROM public.users</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  WITH (replication_origin = &#39;postgres:primary&#39;)</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;">`</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">)</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">;</span></span></code></pre></div><p>Behavior:</p><ul><li>the view is queryable locally as <code>public.users</code></li><li>each read resolves through the upstream client at runtime</li><li>rows are not copied into local table storage</li></ul><p>Use this when you do not need an offline copy.</p><h3 id="materialized-views" tabindex="-1"><code>materialized</code> views <a class="header-anchor" href="#materialized-views" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;`materialized` views&quot;">​</a></h3><p><code>materialized</code> views pull origin rows into local storage:</p><div class="language-js"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang">js</span><pre class="shiki material-theme-palenight vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;font-style:italic;">await</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> db</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">.</span><span style="color:#82AAFF;">query</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">(</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">`</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW public.users AS</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  SELECT * FROM public.users</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  WITH (replication_origin = &#39;postgres:primary&#39;)</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;">`</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">)</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">;</span></span></code></pre></div><p>Use this when:</p><ul><li>offline reads matter</li><li>local latency matters</li><li>periodic reconciliation is enough</li></ul><h3 id="realtime-views" tabindex="-1"><code>realtime</code> views <a class="header-anchor" href="#realtime-views" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;`realtime` views&quot;">​</a></h3><p><code>realtime</code> views materialize locally and then stay synchronized:</p><div class="language-js"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang">js</span><pre class="shiki material-theme-palenight vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;font-style:italic;">await</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> db</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">.</span><span style="color:#82AAFF;">query</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">(</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">`</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  CREATE REALTIME VIEW public.posts AS</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  SELECT * FROM public.posts</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#C3E88D;">  WITH (replication_origin = &#39;postgres:primary&#39;)</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#89DDFF;">`</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">)</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">;</span></span></code></pre></div><p>Behavior:</p><ul><li>rows are copied into the local view</li><li>the view stays subscribed to origin commits</li><li>inbound origin changes automatically apply to the local copy</li></ul><p>Use this when you want local querying and continuous alignment.</p><h2 id="replication-options" tabindex="-1">Replication options <a class="header-anchor" href="#replication-options" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Replication options&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Besides <code>replication_origin</code> and <code>replication_mode</code>, FlashQL supports additional replication options.</p><p>These fall into two groups:</p><ul><li>query-planning options for federated runtime execution</li><li>conflict and outbound-write options for replicated writable views</li></ul><h2 id="join-related-options" tabindex="-1">Join-related options <a class="header-anchor" href="#join-related-options" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Join-related options&quot;">​</a></h2><p>These options affect how FlashQL plans federated join work:</p><ul><li><code>join_pushdown_size</code></li><li><code>join_memoization</code></li></ul><p>Example:</p><div class="language-sql"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang">sql</span><pre class="shiki material-theme-palenight vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span style="color:#F78C6C;">CREATE</span><span style="color:#F78C6C;"> VIEW</span><span style="color:#82AAFF;"> public</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">.posts </span><span style="color:#F78C6C;">AS</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#F78C6C;">SELECT</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;"> *</span><span style="color:#F78C6C;"> FROM</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> public.blog</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#F78C6C;">WITH</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> (</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#BABED8;">  replication_origin </span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">=</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;"> &#39;</span><span style="color:#C3E88D;">postgres:primary</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">&#39;</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">,</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#BABED8;">  join_pushdown_size </span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">=</span><span style="color:#F78C6C;"> 10</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">,</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#BABED8;">  join_memoization </span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">=</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> TRUE</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#BABED8;">);</span></span></code></pre></div><p>Practical meaning:</p><ul><li><code>join_pushdown_size</code> controls how aggressively FlashQL should push join work toward the origin side when federated execution is possible</li><li><code>join_memoization</code> controls whether equivalent join work should be memoized to avoid repeating fetches</li></ul><p>These matter most for runtime federation, where reads are resolved on demand across local and origin relations.</p><h2 id="writable-origin-backed-views" tabindex="-1">Writable origin-backed views <a class="header-anchor" href="#writable-origin-backed-views" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Writable origin-backed views&quot;">​</a></h2><p>FlashQL also extends updateable-view semantics so that writes against a local view can become writes against the origin relation.</p><p>The important idea is:</p><ul><li>you write to the view</li><li>FlashQL derives how that view maps back to the origin relation</li><li>the view&#39;s write policy decides what local state should do before the origin acknowledges</li></ul><p>This works best for direct and analyzable projection views.</p><h2 id="write-policies" tabindex="-1">Write policies <a class="header-anchor" href="#write-policies" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Write policies&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Replicated views support two write policies:</p><ul><li><code>origin_first</code></li><li><code>local_first</code></li></ul><h3 id="origin-first" tabindex="-1"><code>origin_first</code> <a class="header-anchor" href="#origin-first" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;`origin_first`&quot;">​</a></h3><ul><li>local writes queue outbound work</li><li>the visible local row does not change inline</li><li>inbound origin commits later materialize the authoritative row state</li></ul><h3 id="local-first" tabindex="-1"><code>local_first</code> <a class="header-anchor" href="#local-first" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;`local_first`&quot;">​</a></h3><ul><li>local writes stage row changes immediately</li><li>rows carry <code>__staged = true</code> until authoritative inbound arrives</li><li>outbound work is still queued and sent in the background</li></ul><p>In both models, inbound origin commits remain the authoritative source of row state.</p><h2 id="the-staged-system-column" tabindex="-1">The <code>__staged</code> system column <a class="header-anchor" href="#the-staged-system-column" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;The `__staged` system column&quot;">​</a></h2><p>FlashQL exposes a predictable <code>__staged</code> boolean on synced views.</p><p>Its meaning is:</p><ul><li><code>false</code> this row is authoritative locally</li><li><code>true</code> this row was born or changed locally and is still staged</li></ul><h2 id="upstream-mvcc-key" tabindex="-1"><code>upstream_mvcc_key</code> <a class="header-anchor" href="#upstream-mvcc-key" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;`upstream_mvcc_key`&quot;">​</a></h2><p>For replicated writable views, the other important knob is <code>upstream_mvcc_key</code>.</p><p>Example:</p><div class="language-sql"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang">sql</span><pre class="shiki material-theme-palenight vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span style="color:#F78C6C;">CREATE</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> REALTIME VIEW public.users </span><span style="color:#F78C6C;">AS</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#F78C6C;">SELECT</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;"> *</span><span style="color:#F78C6C;"> FROM</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> public.users</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#F78C6C;">WITH</span><span style="color:#BABED8;"> (</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#BABED8;">  replication_origin </span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">=</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;"> &#39;</span><span style="color:#C3E88D;">postgres:primary</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">&#39;</span><span style="color:#BABED8;">,</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#BABED8;">  upstream_mvcc_key </span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">=</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;"> &#39;</span><span style="color:#C3E88D;">XMIN</span><span style="color:#89DDFF;">&#39;</span></span>\n<span class="line"><span style="color:#BABED8;">);</span></span></code></pre></div><p>This tells FlashQL which origin-side version token should be used to condition outbound writes.</p><p>That is what makes conflict handling predictable instead of silent last-writer-wins overwrites.</p><p>For PostgreSQL- and FlashQL-backed origins, FlashQL can often default this to <code>XMIN</code>.</p><h2 id="conflict-expectations" tabindex="-1">Conflict expectations <a class="header-anchor" href="#conflict-expectations" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Conflict expectations&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Conflict handling is part of the view definition story, not an afterthought.</p><p>That is why replicated writable views can carry:</p><ul><li><code>write_policy</code></li><li><code>upstream_mvcc_key</code></li></ul><p>Those options let FlashQL do two things:</p><ul><li>decide what the user sees locally before origin acknowledgment</li><li>decide how outbound writes should be conditionally applied at the origin</li></ul><p>The practical result is predictable conflict behavior rather than silent overwrites.</p><p>The full version-token and queue-state story is covered in:</p><ul><li><a href="/flashql/conflicts">Conflict Handling</a></li></ul><h2 id="writeability-expectations" tabindex="-1">Writeability expectations <a class="header-anchor" href="#writeability-expectations" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Writeability expectations&quot;">​</a></h2><p>FlashQL&#39;s writable views are recognizable as updateable views, but they are not claiming to implement every possible SQL-standard or trigger-driven updatable-view pattern.</p><p>Today, the strongest writeable and syncable shapes are:</p><ul><li>direct relation references</li><li>simple analyzable projections over one writable source relation</li></ul><p>And some valid view definitions are intentionally non-updatable for replicated write paths, especially:</p><ul><li><code>UNION</code>-backed views</li><li><code>VALUES</code>-backed views</li><li>more complex <code>CTE</code>-driven shapes</li></ul><h2 id="putting-it-together" tabindex="-1">Putting it together <a class="header-anchor" href="#putting-it-together" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Putting it together&quot;">​</a></h2><p>So the full foreign I/O story is:</p><ul><li><code>replication_origin</code> decides whether the view is local or origin-backed</li><li><code>replication_mode</code> decides whether origin data stays runtime-only, cached, or continuously synced</li><li>join-related replication options tune federated runtime execution</li><li>write-related replication options define local write visibility and conflict behavior</li></ul><p>That is why views are the center of FlashQL federation and sync rather than just one piece of it.</p><h2 id="related-docs" tabindex="-1">Related docs <a class="header-anchor" href="#related-docs" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Related docs&quot;">​</a></h2><ul><li><a href="/flashql/sync">FlashQL Sync</a></li><li><a href="/flashql/conflicts">Conflict Handling</a></li><li><a href="/flashql/sync-patterns">Sync Integration Patterns</a></li></ul><h2 id="appendix-a-join-options" tabindex="-1">Appendix A: <code>join_*</code> options <a class="header-anchor" href="#appendix-a-join-options" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Appendix A: `join_*` options&quot;">​</a></h2><p>The <code>join_*</code> options are runtime-federation controls.</p><p>They are relevant when a view is being resolved on demand across local and origin relations. In other words, they are runtime-view concerns.</p><p>The main ones are:</p><ul><li><code>join_pushdown_size</code></li><li><code>join_memoization</code></li></ul><h3 id="join-pushdown-size" tabindex="-1"><code>join_pushdown_size</code> <a class="header-anchor" href="#join-pushdown-size" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;`join_pushdown_size`&quot;">​</a></h3><p>This controls how aggressively FlashQL should push join work toward the origin side when federated execution is possible.</p><p>Higher values generally mean:</p><ul><li>more origin-side work can be attempted</li><li>fewer round trips may be needed</li></ul><p>Lower values generally mean:</p><ul><li>FlashQL keeps more of the join work local</li><li>planning stays conservative</li></ul><h3 id="join-memoization" tabindex="-1"><code>join_memoization</code> <a class="header-anchor" href="#join-memoization" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;`join_memoization`&quot;">​</a></h3><p>This controls whether repeated federated join work should be memoized.</p><p>That can help when:</p><ul><li>the same local-to-origin join work repeats</li><li>the same lookup pattern would otherwise refetch equivalent origin subsets</li></ul><h3 id="important-scope-note" tabindex="-1">Important scope note <a class="header-anchor" href="#important-scope-note" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Important scope note&quot;">​</a></h3><p>These options are about federated runtime reads.</p><p>They are not the knobs that define:</p><ul><li>materialization</li><li>realtime synchronization</li><li>outbound write semantics</li><li>conflict detection</li></ul><p>Those belong to the sync and writable-view story instead.</p><h2 id="appendix-b-mvcc-in-the-sync-story" tabindex="-1">Appendix B: MVCC in the sync story <a class="header-anchor" href="#appendix-b-mvcc-in-the-sync-story" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Appendix B: MVCC in the sync story&quot;">​</a></h2><p>The conflict story for FlashQL sync leans on an origin-side version token.</p><p>That is what <code>upstream_mvcc_key</code> configures.</p><h3 id="why-postgresql-and-flashql-fit-well-here" tabindex="-1">Why PostgreSQL and FlashQL fit well here <a class="header-anchor" href="#why-postgresql-and-flashql-fit-well-here" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Why PostgreSQL and FlashQL fit well here&quot;">​</a></h3><p>Both PostgreSQL and FlashQL have MVCC-oriented row versioning stories.</p><p>In practice, that gives FlashQL a natural token to use when it needs to say:</p><blockquote><p>&quot;apply this write only if the row is still the version I saw&quot;</p></blockquote><p>For PostgreSQL and FlashQL origins, that token is often <code>XMIN</code>.</p><h3 id="what-flashql-does-with-that-token" tabindex="-1">What FlashQL does with that token <a class="header-anchor" href="#what-flashql-does-with-that-token" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;What FlashQL does with that token&quot;">​</a></h3><p>For a replicated writable view, FlashQL can:</p><ol><li>project the origin version token into local row state</li><li>carry that token with the queued outbound write</li><li>apply the outbound write conditionally at the origin</li></ol><p>If the origin row version no longer matches, the write can be classified as a conflict instead of silently overwriting newer state.</p><h3 id="why-upstream-mvcc-key-exists" tabindex="-1">Why <code>upstream_mvcc_key</code> exists <a class="header-anchor" href="#why-upstream-mvcc-key-exists" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Why `upstream_mvcc_key` exists&quot;">​</a></h3><p>Not every origin exposes the same version token shape.</p><p>That is why the view-level <code>upstream_mvcc_key</code> option exists:</p><ul><li>it makes the token configurable</li><li>it lets the same conflict model adapt to different origin systems</li></ul><p>For the full conflict story, see <a href="/flashql/conflicts">Conflict Handling</a>.</p>', 173)
  ])]);
}
const foreignIo = /* @__PURE__ */ _export_sfc(_sfc_main, [["render", _sfc_render]]);
export {
  __pageData,
  foreignIo as default
};
